	url = {https://www.atmos-chem-phys-discuss.net/acp-2018-1112/},
	doi = {https://doi.org/10.5194/acp-2018-1112},
	abstract = {{\textless}p{\textgreater}{\textless}strong{\textgreater}Abstract.{\textless}/strong{\textgreater} With the completion of the Beijing Five-year Clean Air Action Plan by the end of 2017, the annual mean PM$_{\textrm{2.5}}$ concentrations in Beijing dropped dramatically to 58.0 μg/m$^{\textrm{3}}$ in 2017 from 89.5 μg/m$^{\textrm{3}}$ in 2013. However, controversies exist to argue that favorable meteorological conditions in 2017 that helped pollution dispersion were the major factor for such rapid decrease in PM$_{\textrm{2.5}}$ concentrations. To comprehensively evaluate this five-year plan, we employed Kolmogorov-Zurbenko (KZ) filtering and a WRF-CMAQ model to quantify the relative contribution of meteorological conditions and the control of anthropogenic emissions to PM$_{\textrm{2.5}}$ reduction in Beijing from 2013 to 2017. For these five years, the relative contribution of emission-reduction measures to the decrease of PM$_{\textrm{2.5}}$ concentrations in Beijing calculated by KZ filtering and the WRF-CMAQ model was 80.6 \% and 78.6 \% respectively. The WRF-CMAQ model further revealed that local and regional emission-reduction measures contributed to 53.7 \% and 24.9 \% of the PM$_{\textrm{2.5}}$ reduction respectively. For local emission-reduction measures, the regulation of coal boilers, increasing clean fuels for residential use, industrial restructuring, the regulation of raise dust and vehicle emissions contributed to 20.1 \%, 17.4 \%, 10.8 \%, 3.0 \% and 2.4 \% of PM$_{\textrm{2.5}}$ reduction respectively. Both models suggested that the control of anthropogenic emissions contributed to around 80 \% of the total decrease in PM$_{\textrm{2.5}}$ concentrations in Beijing, indicating that emission control was crucial for the notable improvement in air quality in Beijing from 2013 to 2017. Therefore, such long-term air quality clean plan should be continued for the future years to further reduce PM$_{\textrm{2.5}}$ concentrations in Beijing. Considering that different emission-reduction measures exert distinct effects on PM$_{\textrm{2.5}}$ reduction and existing emission-reduction measures work poorly to reduce ozone concentrations, future strategies for emission-reduction should be designed and implemented accordingly.{\textless}/p{\textgreater}},
