nd the a priori used in the retrieval compared to the relatively small field-of-view of the Pandora instrument. On the other hand, TROPOMI slightly overestimates (within the retrieval uncertainties) relatively small {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}NO$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} total columns. Replacing the coarse a priori {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}NO$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} profiles with high-resolution profiles from the CAMS chemical transport model improves the agreement between TROPOMI and Pandora total columns for episodes of {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}NO$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} enhancement. When only the low values of {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}NO$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} total columns or the whole dataset are taken into account, the mean bias slightly increases. The change in bias remains mostly within the uncertainties.{\textless}/p{\textgreater} {\textless}p{\textgreater}We also analyse the consistency between satellite-based data and in situ {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}NO$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} surface concentrations measured at the Helsinki–Kumpula air quality station (located a few metres from the Pandora spectrometer). We find similar day-to-day variability between TROPOMI, Pandora and in situ measurements, with {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}NO$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} enhancements observed during the same days. Both satellite- and ground-based data show a similar weekly cycle, with lower {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}NO$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} levels during the weekend compared to the weekdays as a result of reduced emissions from traffic and industrial activities (as expected in urban sites). The TROPOMI {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgrea