	abstract = {{\textless}p{\textgreater}{\textless}strong class="journal-contentHeaderColor"{\textgreater}Abstract.{\textless}/strong{\textgreater} We describe the design and performance of a lightweight broadband cavity-enhanced spectrometer for measurement of NO$_{\textrm{2}}$ on uncrewed aerial vehicles and light aircraft. The instrument uses an LED centered at 457 nm, high-finesse mirrors (reflectivity=0.999963 at 450 nm), and a grating spectrometer to determine optical extinction coefficients between 430\&ndash;476 nm, which are fit with custom spectral fitting software and published absorption cross sections. The instrument weighs 3.05 kg and has power consumption less than 35 W at 25 \&deg;C. A ground calibration unit provides helium and zero air flows to periodically determine the reflectivity of the cavity mirrors using known Rayleigh scattering cross sections. The precision (1\&sigma;) for laboratory measurements is 43 ppt NO$_{\textrm{2}}$ in 1 s and 7 ppt NO$_{\textrm{2}}$ in 30 s. Measurement of air with known NO$_{\textrm{2}}$ mixing ratios in the range of 0\&ndash;70 ppb agreed with the known values within 0.3 \% (slope=0.997\&plusmn;0.007; r$^{\textrm{2}}$=0.99983). We demonstrate instrument performance using vertical profiles of NO$_{\textrm{2}}$ mixing ratio acquired onboard an uncrewed aerial vehicle between 0\&ndash;120 m above ground level in Boulder, Colorado.{\textless}/p{\textgreater}},
