an class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}NO$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} sensors are capable of distinguishing general pollution levels, but they proved unsuitable for accurate measurements, mainly due to significant biases. In order to investigate the long-term stability of the original calibration, the sensors were reinstalled at the calibration site after deployment. Surprisingly, the coefficient of determination and the RMSE of the {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}NO{\textless}/span{\textgreater} sensor remained almost unchanged after more than 1 year of operation. In contrast, the performance of the {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}NO$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} sensors clearly deteriorated as indicated by a higher RMSE (about 7.5 ppb, 10 min mean concentrations) and a lower coefficient of determination ({\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}\textit{R}$^{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}={\textless}/span{\textgreater} 0.59).{\textless}/p{\textgreater}},
